04740nam a22006615i 9780231556118DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022014164  a97802315561187 a10.7312/mang205682doi  a(DE-B1597)649679  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL2274.2.I5bM36 2023 7aLIT0200002bisacsh1 aMangalagiri, Adhira, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStates of Disconnect :bThe China-India Literary Relation in the Twentieth Century /cAdhira Mangalagiri. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b8 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration and Translation -- tIntroduction: States of Disconnect -- tONE Anatomy of Antagonism: The Indian Policeman in Chinese Literature -- tTWO Revolution Redux: Agyeya’s China Stories -- tTHREE Dialogue and Its Discontents: 1950s Cultural Diplomacy Untold -- tFOUR Word and World in Crisis: Hindi Texts of 1962 -- tFIVE On Correspondence: Lu Xun and Premchand -- tConclusion: A Comparatist’s Guide to Disconnect -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an interconnected world, literature moves through transnational networks, crosses borders, and bridges diverse cultures. In these ways, literature can bring people closer together. Today, as hopes for globalization wane and exclusionary nationalism is on the march, can literature still offer new ways of relating with others? Comparative literature has long been under the spell of circulation, contact, connectivity, and mobility—what if it instead sought out their antitheses?States of Disconnect examines the breakdown of transnationalism through readings of literary texts that express aversion to pairing ideas of China and India. Focusing on practices of comparison, Adhira Mangalagiri considers how these texts articulate the undesirability or impossibility of relating with national others, tracing portrayals of violence, silence, and distance. She proposes the concept of “disconnect”: a crisis of transnationalism perceptible in moments when a connection is severed, interrupted, or disavowed. Despite their apparent insularity, texts of disconnect offer possibilities for relating ethically across national borders while resisting both narrow nationalisms and globalized habits of thought. Reading a variety of largely untranslated twentieth-century Chinese and Hindi short stories, novels, and poems, Mangalagiri develops three new strategies for comparison—friction, ellipses, and contingency—that together comprise a critical vocabulary of disconnect. Foregrounding transnationalism’s discontents, States of Disconnect offers a different path by which literary texts can cultivate a critical sensibility for making sense of a world rife with division.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChinese literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aComparative literaturexChinese and Indic. 0aComparative literaturexIndic and Chinese. 0aIndic literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aTransnationalism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/mang2056840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231556118423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231556118/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHA